        <h2 class="h-md">Programmatic SEO, <span class="accent">answered.</span></h2>
        <p>Common questions about pSEO tools and strategy. More? Email <a href="mailto:founder@thestacc.com">founder@thestacc.com</a>.</p>
        <p style="margin-top: 24px;">See more: <a href="/reviews/" class="accent">read tool reviews</a>, <a href="/alternatives/" class="accent">compare alternatives</a>, or <a href="/pricing/" class="accent">view pricing</a>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is programmatic SEO black hat?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">No. pSEO is a method, not manipulation. Google does not penalize pSEO. Google penalizes thin, duplicate, auto-generated content that adds no value. Pages with unique data answering real queries rank comparably to hand-written pages.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does Google penalize programmatic SEO?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Google penalizes thin, duplicate, and low-value content regardless of creation method. The risk with pSEO involves accidentally producing thin pages at scale. Strong templates and unique data produce well-ranking pages. The method itself is not penalized.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between programmatic SEO and autoblogging?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">pSEO generates pages from structured data and templates — location, comparison, and directory pages. Autoblogging generates full articles at scale from keywords or topics. There's overlap; both can serve pSEO strategies depending on the goal.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do I need technical skills for programmatic SEO?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">It depends on the tool. PageFactory, Typemat, and Whalesync are no-code. Byword requires only a keyword list. theStacc requires nothing — it's fully managed. Airtable + CMS stacks require moderate technical ability. SEOmatic requires the most setup knowledge.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the cheapest way to start with programmatic SEO?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Airtable (free) + WordPress (free) + Make.com ($9/mo) = $9/month for a functional pSEO stack, requiring 15-25 hours of setup. If your time is worth more than a few dollars per hour, PageFactory ($29/mo) or theStacc ($99/mo) provide faster time-to-value.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I use programmatic SEO for local businesses?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Generating "best [service] in [city]" pages across hundreds of cities is a common pSEO use case. theStacc handles content-based local pSEO automatically. PageFactory and Typemat handle template-based location pages from a spreadsheet.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I prevent my pSEO pages from looking spammy?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Three rules: every page contains unique, substantive content beyond template swaps; add real value beyond competitor pages through local data or original analysis; and only generate pages your data actually supports. Thin templates scaled to 10,000 pages is what gets penalized, not the method.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
